NEWCASTLE DISEASE, ORNAMENTAL BIRDS - NETHERLANDS
*************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.healthnet.org/programs/promed.html>
Date: Sat, 16 Jan 1999 15:53:05 -0800
From: Dorothy Preslar <dpreslar@fas.org>
Source: Office International des Epizooties, 15 Jan 1999

See also: 24 April 1998, 22 August 1997
(Date of last previously reported outbreak: August 1997).
Emergency reportText of an e-mail received on 14 January 1999 from Dr
C.C.J.M. van der Meijs, Chief Veterinary Officer, Ministry of Agriculture,
Nature Management and Fisheries, The Hague:
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory, following suspicion.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 21 December 1998.
Location: city of Drachten, Friesland province (53o 07' N - 6o 05' E)
No. of outbreaks: 1
Description of affected population: mixed flock with different species of
tropical and ornamental birds owned by a trader in birds. The disease has
been diagnosed in cockatiels (_Nymphicus hollandicus_).
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
susceptible: 5,771
cases ...
deaths 0
destroyed 5,771
slaughtered 0
Diagnosis:
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: ID-DLO Lelystad (Central Veterinary
Institute).
B. Diagnostic tests used: haemagglutination reaction, PCR(1), ICPI(2) (= 1.5).
Source of agent / origin of infection: unknown.
Control measures during reporting period: stamping out; tracing on and
tracing back.
(1) PCR: polymerase chain reaction.
(2) ICPI: intracerebral pathogenicity index.
--
ProMED-mail
e-mail: promed@usa.healthnet.org
